WEBVTT

00:05.339 --> 00:08.050
<i>[exciting music]</i>

00:08.050 --> 00:13.222
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:13.222 --> 00:16.308
<i>- My name</i>
<i>is Bill van Heteren.</i>

00:16.308 --> 00:18.727
When I make a knife,
it's almost like a living being.

00:18.727 --> 00:21.730
<i>At the point of heat treat,</i>
<i>where it takes on a soul,</i>

00:21.730 --> 00:23.982
<i>I don't even leave</i>
<i>the blade in the shop.</i>

00:23.982 --> 00:25.943
I bring it in the house
with me at night.

00:25.943 --> 00:28.153
<i>- My name's Andrew Woznak.</i>

00:28.153 --> 00:30.864
I would consider myself
the underdog coming in here.

00:30.864 --> 00:33.200
<i>A little under two years'</i>
<i>experience, it's not a lot.</i>

00:33.200 --> 00:35.410
<i>But give me</i>
<i>a block of steel,</i>

00:35.410 --> 00:37.454
I can do anything
that I want with it.

00:37.454 --> 00:39.373
<i>- My name's Mike Bailey.</i>

00:39.373 --> 00:41.792
<i>There is a lot of magic</i>
<i>in bladesmithing.</i>

00:41.792 --> 00:43.502
Metal came from space.

00:43.502 --> 00:45.671
<i>This is the elements</i>
<i>of the universe.</i>

00:45.671 --> 00:47.923
Also, I get to play
with fire and hit things.

00:47.923 --> 00:50.008
I mean, where else?

00:50.008 --> 00:51.927
- My name's Alex Reese,
and I forge blades

00:51.927 --> 00:54.012
on nights and weekends.

00:54.012 --> 00:55.889
<i>I used to make hammers</i>
<i>and tongs for bladesmiths,</i>

00:55.889 --> 00:57.391
<i>and I got bit by the bug.</i>

00:57.391 --> 00:59.810
<i>Describe myself</i>
<i>in three words?</i>

00:59.810 --> 01:03.438
Loves to forge.

01:03.438 --> 01:05.190
- Bladesmiths,
welcome to the Forge.

01:05.190 --> 01:06.733
You're here for three rounds

01:06.733 --> 01:08.485
of edged-weapon-making
competition

01:08.485 --> 01:10.779
designed to push your skills
to the limit.

01:10.779 --> 01:12.948
At the end of each round,

01:12.948 --> 01:14.866
you'll be presenting your work
to our panel of expert judges.

01:14.866 --> 01:16.702
Let's meet them now.

01:16.702 --> 01:19.913
Up first, ABS Mastersmith
J. Neilsen...

01:19.913 --> 01:22.249
Next, historic weapons
recreation specialist

01:22.249 --> 01:24.042
David Baker...

01:24.042 --> 01:26.837
And last, Kali martial artist
Doug Marcaida.

01:26.837 --> 01:28.589
I'm sure you noticed
that your anvils

01:28.589 --> 01:31.717
are conspicuously
absent any steel.

01:31.717 --> 01:33.885
That's because in the first
round of competition,

01:33.885 --> 01:35.429
we're giving you this...

01:35.429 --> 01:41.101
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:43.103 --> 01:46.023
A huge pile
of 5160 spring steel

01:46.023 --> 01:47.733
that you got
to figure out how to forge

01:47.733 --> 01:51.737
into a signature blade
in your signature style.

01:51.737 --> 01:54.656
- I'm just floored that this is
gonna be my challenge.

01:54.656 --> 01:58.618
I wanted spring,
but not that big.

01:58.618 --> 02:00.495
<i>- The length</i>
<i>of your blades must be</i>

02:00.495 --> 02:02.372
<i>between 10 and 13inches.</i>

02:02.372 --> 02:03.665
<i>The overall length</i>
<i>of your weapon</i>

02:03.665 --> 02:05.709
<i>must not exceed 22 inches.</i>

02:05.709 --> 02:10.005
You must include a through tang
in your blade's design.

02:10.005 --> 02:11.673
Keep in mind that
in the second round,

02:11.673 --> 02:13.342
you'll be attaching handles
to your blades

02:13.342 --> 02:15.302
to turn them
into fully functional weapons

02:15.302 --> 02:17.012
that will tested
for strength and durability

02:17.012 --> 02:19.056
in a steel drum stab,

02:19.056 --> 02:22.601
and for edge retention
in a leather sandbag slice.

02:22.601 --> 02:24.853
You will have ten minutes
to work on your design.

02:24.853 --> 02:27.522
You have three hours
to forge your blades.

02:27.522 --> 02:31.401
Good luck. Your ten-minute
design window starts now.

02:31.401 --> 02:35.364
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:35.364 --> 02:37.324
<i>- My first instinct is to do</i>
<i>what I know best.</i>

02:37.324 --> 02:40.577
I'm gonna make
a big recurve Bowie.

02:40.577 --> 02:42.829
<i>It's gonna be beefy</i>
<i>enough to pierce.</i>

02:42.829 --> 02:45.999
It's gonna hold up
its edge, hopefully.

02:45.999 --> 02:47.084
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:47.084 --> 02:48.794
<i>I got into blacksmithing</i>

02:48.794 --> 02:50.962
because I saw some
decorative stuff online,

02:50.962 --> 02:53.674
<i>and I thought to myself,</i>
<i>"Maybe I can make it."</i>

02:53.674 --> 02:56.718
[odd voice] The stars aligned
to put me here.

02:56.718 --> 02:58.845
[normal voice]
What was that voice?

02:58.845 --> 03:01.348
That was like I turned into
a little Walken. It's like...

03:01.348 --> 03:03.141
[imitating Walken] The stars
aligned to put me here.

03:03.141 --> 03:04.768
You know?

03:04.768 --> 03:06.812
- I'm gonna make
a recurve camp knife.

03:06.812 --> 03:08.980
<i>I know they can stab</i>
<i>with the drop point on them.</i>

03:08.980 --> 03:11.358
<i>I want something with nice</i>
<i>curves that's good for slicing</i>

03:11.358 --> 03:14.695
and something that I know
will satisfy the obstacles

03:14.695 --> 03:16.530
that they're gonna
be put through.

03:16.530 --> 03:18.990
<i>We're forging spring.</i>

03:18.990 --> 03:21.159
<i>The trickiest part is going</i>
<i>to be getting enough mass</i>

03:21.159 --> 03:22.994
<i>to make a large knife.</i>

03:22.994 --> 03:24.621
<i>It's gonna be a lot</i>
<i>of forge-welding.</i>

03:24.621 --> 03:26.164
And I'm scared.

03:26.164 --> 03:27.916
I don't know
what's gonna happen.

03:27.916 --> 03:29.751
- I'm making a
spear-point Bowie,

03:29.751 --> 03:34.089
because it's a thrusting as well
as a slicing instrument.

03:34.089 --> 03:35.674
<i>I feel this is</i>
<i>a good time for me</i>

03:35.674 --> 03:37.592
<i>to compete</i>
<i>in "Forged in Fire,"</i>

03:37.592 --> 03:40.345
because I have this
knowledge of knife making

03:40.345 --> 03:42.889
that I want to share
with the world.

03:42.889 --> 03:44.933
<i>This is the perfect</i>
<i>opportunity for me</i>

03:44.933 --> 03:47.477
to demonstrate what I know.

03:47.477 --> 03:51.064
- I'm going with a modified
spear-point dagger,

03:51.064 --> 03:54.067
<i>because I think it will do well</i>
<i>with the leather bag slice</i>

03:54.067 --> 03:56.862
<i>and the steel drum stab.</i>

03:56.862 --> 04:00.115
<i>I started a forge in my</i>
<i>backyard about four years ago.</i>

04:00.115 --> 04:02.742
I christened it
"The Leprechaun Lair Forge."

04:02.742 --> 04:04.870
<i>I've been called a leprechaun</i>

04:04.870 --> 04:07.664
<i>'cause I'm a little mischievous</i>
<i>and a little bit devious.</i>

04:07.664 --> 04:10.792
So it kind of stuck.
It just was a great match.

04:10.792 --> 04:13.128
- Bladesmiths, your ten-minute
design window has closed.

04:13.128 --> 04:17.007
Your three-hour forge
time starts now.

04:17.007 --> 04:19.509
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:19.509 --> 04:21.720
- There's a few different ways
you could go about

04:21.720 --> 04:24.848
turning this steel
into blade stock.

04:24.848 --> 04:28.018
- It looks like Mike and Alex,
they're grabbing canisters.

04:28.018 --> 04:30.061
- Andrew's got
a canister as well.

04:30.061 --> 04:33.231
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:33.231 --> 04:35.609
- Alex has laid his springs
into his can

04:35.609 --> 04:37.819
like a bunch of cannolis.

04:37.819 --> 04:42.741
And like a cannoli, you can have
voids in those spaces in there

04:42.741 --> 04:44.618
where that powdered steel
didn't get to, you know?

04:44.618 --> 04:46.661
- Yeah, if you don't have
that powdered steel

04:46.661 --> 04:48.663
go all the way up to the top,
you're gonna have air gaps.

04:48.663 --> 04:51.374
- Yeah. What he should've done
is just stood 'em up.

04:51.374 --> 04:53.335
<i>- If the canister works,</i>

04:53.335 --> 04:55.462
I think I'm gonna
come out ahead.

04:55.462 --> 04:57.464
Now we wait.

04:57.464 --> 05:00.675
- Bill's stripping on the floor.
- Take it off, baby!

05:00.675 --> 05:02.594
- [humming sultry tune]
- Yeah, buddy!

05:02.594 --> 05:04.095
all: Whoo!
- Yeah!

05:04.095 --> 05:06.056
[laughter]

05:06.056 --> 05:08.809
- I really like working
with 5160 steel.

05:08.809 --> 05:11.728
<i>But I've never worked</i>
<i>with springs before.</i>

05:11.728 --> 05:15.148
They're tiny. They're springy.

05:15.148 --> 05:16.316
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:16.316 --> 05:17.859
- Problem's gonna be,

05:17.859 --> 05:19.486
is forcing
that all into one piece

05:19.486 --> 05:21.279
and not building up
so much forge scale

05:21.279 --> 05:23.156
that it won't weld together.

05:23.156 --> 05:24.866
- Well, that's the thing.
I mean, they get too much

05:24.866 --> 05:26.743
of a carbon buildup on them,
it's gonna be a problem.

05:26.743 --> 05:28.578
- I feel that the San Mai
approach

05:28.578 --> 05:30.789
is the best way to go
for me.

05:30.789 --> 05:33.750
<i>I'm working with the springs</i>
<i>to try and get them uncoiled</i>

05:33.750 --> 05:36.837
and get them into a bundle
and then forge weld them.

05:36.837 --> 05:39.172
Let's bundle this bitch up.

05:39.172 --> 05:41.091
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:41.091 --> 05:43.343
<i>- I'm gonna give canister</i>
<i>Damascus a shot.</i>

05:43.343 --> 05:46.179
But I've never done one before,
so it's a little intimidating.

05:46.179 --> 05:47.848
Ooh.

05:47.848 --> 05:49.641
- What I think these guys
are going for is,

05:49.641 --> 05:51.142
if they stretch
out the springs,

05:51.142 --> 05:52.894
it's easier to get powder--

05:52.894 --> 05:55.146
- Powder all the way
around that material.

05:55.146 --> 05:58.108
- If I don't put space
between each coil,

05:58.108 --> 06:01.194
then I could end up
with delamination or cold shut.

06:01.194 --> 06:03.113
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:03.113 --> 06:06.283
- I've never welded before,
so this is fun.

06:06.283 --> 06:09.035
- Okay, so we have a smith here
that does not know how to weld.

06:09.035 --> 06:10.620
- Come on, Andrew.
- Uh-oh.

06:10.620 --> 06:13.248
- Yeah, turn it on first.
Turn it on helps.

06:13.248 --> 06:15.083
- Let's see if he gets
the hang of it.

06:15.083 --> 06:17.002
- [bleep].

06:17.002 --> 06:18.670
Shoot!

06:18.670 --> 06:21.673
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:21.673 --> 06:23.925
<i>Can't see through the visor,</i>

06:23.925 --> 06:27.053
and I'm trying to hook
the welder up to the steel

06:27.053 --> 06:30.015
and then quickly
pull down my mask,

06:30.015 --> 06:32.100
'cause I can't see anything.

06:32.100 --> 06:33.393
Mother--

06:33.393 --> 06:34.561
It's ugly.

06:34.561 --> 06:36.396
♪ ♪

06:36.396 --> 06:37.772
[bleep].

06:37.772 --> 06:39.316
- He just dumped his canister

06:39.316 --> 06:40.901
and spilled about
half his power out.

06:40.901 --> 06:42.319
- Oh, jeez.
- Oh, man.

06:42.319 --> 06:44.237
<i>- Yeah, I'm pretty bummed,</i>

06:44.237 --> 06:46.364
<i>but there's no way</i>
<i>this is gonna happen.</i>

06:46.364 --> 06:48.700
I'm not gonna even waste time to
do something that I don't know.

06:48.700 --> 06:50.577
<i>I got to do a 180,</i>

06:50.577 --> 06:53.496
and try to make up
for all this lost time now.

06:53.496 --> 06:57.083
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:57.083 --> 06:58.960
- Mike's just heating
that spring with the rosebuds,

06:58.960 --> 07:00.629
just whap.

07:00.629 --> 07:03.298
It's like he's starting
a lawnmower.

07:03.298 --> 07:05.133
- Bladesmiths!

07:05.133 --> 07:08.219
You only have
2 1/2 hours remaining

07:08.219 --> 07:10.180
to finish those blades!

07:10.180 --> 07:13.558
- I'm feeling invigorated
from this challenge.

07:13.558 --> 07:16.686
<i>Five years ago, I got knocked</i>
<i>off the top of a truck,</i>

07:16.686 --> 07:20.940
broke my neck and back
and fractured my skull.

07:20.940 --> 07:24.944
So I'm planning on going for
the moon, because I got lucky.

07:24.944 --> 07:27.947
I'm alive. I'm here.

07:27.947 --> 07:30.867
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:30.867 --> 07:32.535
- Fire, fire. Coming through.

07:32.535 --> 07:34.871
- Alex heading over
to the press.

07:34.871 --> 07:37.624
- It's hot, but I don't know
if the core is hot enough.

07:37.624 --> 07:39.626
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:39.626 --> 07:40.627
- [bleep].

07:40.627 --> 07:42.379
Oh, crap.

07:42.379 --> 07:43.963
- Oh, it looks like
he popped the end of

07:43.963 --> 07:45.715
of the can
right off there, J.

07:45.715 --> 07:48.093
- Yeah.

07:48.093 --> 07:50.178
<i>- I'm freaking out, because</i>
<i>if that didn't consolidate,</i>

07:50.178 --> 07:52.889
I no longer have an oxygen-free
environment in there.

07:52.889 --> 07:55.558
I'm not gonna be able
to weld this thing solid.

07:55.558 --> 07:57.894
<i>So I get it</i>
<i>back in the forge,</i>

07:57.894 --> 08:00.230
work it a little bit more
with the press.

08:00.230 --> 08:02.190
<i>I go to the chop saw.</i>

08:02.190 --> 08:04.150
This is what
it comes down to.

08:04.150 --> 08:06.319
I need to make sure
that that thing is solid.

08:06.319 --> 08:09.614
- And that's Alex chopping off
the end of his billet,

08:09.614 --> 08:11.491
getting a look
at what's going on inside.

08:11.491 --> 08:13.118
- It's a good idea
at this point.

08:13.118 --> 08:16.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:16.246 --> 08:19.624
- That's one solid
piece of steel.

08:19.624 --> 08:21.084
Yes!

08:21.084 --> 08:23.253
Solid.

08:23.253 --> 08:25.004
- I don't have time
for any more mess-ups.

08:25.004 --> 08:26.965
I've already messed up once.

08:26.965 --> 08:29.259
<i>Plan B is to get these</i>
<i>coil springs welded up,</i>

08:29.259 --> 08:31.720
and I'm gonna get
a piece of mild steel,

08:31.720 --> 08:34.723
wrap it around that, weld it
together for some San Mai.

08:34.723 --> 08:39.269
- He's got one long wire,
but so little metal.

08:39.269 --> 08:41.020
- I've got
my springs welded up,

08:41.020 --> 08:43.231
so now I start
getting my mild steel

08:43.231 --> 08:45.442
<i>into a sandwich shape.</i>

08:45.442 --> 08:47.861
I need to get it nice and tight
to where it's not gonna fall out

08:47.861 --> 08:49.779
when I go to set
my first weld.

08:49.779 --> 08:51.698
[bleep].

08:51.698 --> 08:54.117
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:54.117 --> 08:56.077
<i>- With the clock</i>
<i>approaching halftime,</i>

08:56.077 --> 08:59.039
the springs aren't
sticking together.

08:59.039 --> 09:00.957
- We've seen in this
competition,

09:00.957 --> 09:04.919
a smith can take a bundle
of material, flux it, whack it,

09:04.919 --> 09:06.838
and all of a sudden,
it's a billet of steel.

09:06.838 --> 09:08.798
Why isn't that working
for Bill?

09:08.798 --> 09:11.134
- He's been having it in
the forge for so long

09:11.134 --> 09:13.011
that I think
he's burning it up.

09:13.011 --> 09:17.849
Scale on 5160 doesn't weld.
- Yeah.

09:17.849 --> 09:19.601
<i>- The springs are reacting</i>

09:19.601 --> 09:21.352
<i>a little bit different</i>
<i>than I thought.</i>

09:21.352 --> 09:23.229
But I'm going to
just forge ahead,

09:23.229 --> 09:25.648
and I feel
anything's possible.

09:25.648 --> 09:27.776
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:27.776 --> 09:30.987
<i>- I finally get my canister</i>
<i>up to temperature.</i>

09:30.987 --> 09:34.908
I get the canister
separated from the billet.

09:34.908 --> 09:38.244
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:38.244 --> 09:40.455
[bleep].
- Oh, God, look at that.

09:40.455 --> 09:43.458
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:43.458 --> 09:46.294
- We just saw
Mike's billet fall apart.

09:46.294 --> 09:48.296
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:48.296 --> 09:51.883
- Yeah, Mike did not let
the canister get hot enough.

09:51.883 --> 09:53.718
Parts of it
are welded together,

09:53.718 --> 09:56.054
but it's not one homogenous
piece of steel yet.

09:56.054 --> 09:58.556
So that's a big problem.
- That's a disaster.

09:58.556 --> 10:00.058
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:00.058 --> 10:01.851
- My heart sinks.

10:01.851 --> 10:04.395
<i>I spent too much time</i>
<i>to start over.</i>

10:04.395 --> 10:06.189
Son of a [bleep].

10:06.189 --> 10:09.359
I failed.
I want to give up.

10:09.359 --> 10:12.112
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:14.197 --> 10:17.033
- We just saw
Mike's billet fall apart.

10:17.033 --> 10:18.910
- Son of a [bleep].

10:18.910 --> 10:22.497
I want to give up.
But I've come all this way.

10:22.497 --> 10:26.668
I'm not gonna go home
because of some weld issues.

10:26.668 --> 10:29.671
- Worse, though, he's just
welded that crumbling block

10:29.671 --> 10:31.256
onto a worse one.

10:31.256 --> 10:32.465
- Well, yeah.
That's the problem.

10:32.465 --> 10:34.467
Mike put it back into the forge,

10:34.467 --> 10:36.719
and when you heat something,
it starts expanding.

10:36.719 --> 10:38.555
It's not fused
into one solid piece.

10:38.555 --> 10:40.557
It's gonna start falling apart.
- Falls apart.

10:40.557 --> 10:42.934
- [bleep].

10:42.934 --> 10:45.979
<i>So I have to go to the press</i>
<i>to be able to get it to weld.</i>

10:45.979 --> 10:48.314
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:48.314 --> 10:51.317
- He's flatting it out.
The question mark's gonna be

10:51.317 --> 10:55.572
when he turns it on its side
and presses down.

10:55.572 --> 10:58.491
That's when we might just
see it all pop and crumble.

10:58.491 --> 11:00.326
<i>- I believe the luck</i>
<i>of the Irish</i>

11:00.326 --> 11:02.328
and the luck of the leprechaun
was on my side.

11:02.328 --> 11:08.251
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:08.251 --> 11:10.170
- Well, so far,

11:10.170 --> 11:12.046
I don't see anything
coming out of his canister.

11:12.046 --> 11:14.465
- No, neither do I.

11:14.465 --> 11:16.885
<i>- My billet starts to draw out.</i>

11:16.885 --> 11:18.136
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:18.136 --> 11:19.721
It starts to weld.

11:19.721 --> 11:21.347
- Having fun yet?

11:21.347 --> 11:23.099
- I'm starting to have
a little fun.

11:23.099 --> 11:24.934
- A little.
- I need more fun, though.

11:24.934 --> 11:27.103
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:27.103 --> 11:28.897
- Andrew's moving some steel.

11:28.897 --> 11:30.815
- The problem with Andrew
moving some steel

11:30.815 --> 11:32.400
is he doesn't have enough steel

11:32.400 --> 11:34.152
to even create an edge
for that thing.

11:34.152 --> 11:35.904
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:35.904 --> 11:37.822
<i>- I know what I'm gonna</i>
<i>end up with,</i>

11:37.822 --> 11:39.657
<i>and it's not gonna be</i>
<i>my style or pretty,</i>

11:39.657 --> 11:43.286
but I just want to get
a knife done at this moment.

11:43.286 --> 11:45.872
<i>- One hour left,</i>
<i>and I've already spent</i>

11:45.872 --> 11:48.124
<i>about 100% of my energy.</i>

11:48.124 --> 11:52.003
Now I'm kicking into overdrive
to get it to shape.

11:52.003 --> 11:55.924
But at this time, I'm spent.

11:55.924 --> 11:58.176
- Mike has physically
hit the wall.

11:58.176 --> 12:01.679
- Mike, you all right?
You gonna make it?

12:01.679 --> 12:04.557
- I try to regain my composure,

12:04.557 --> 12:08.353
<i>do some breathing</i>
<i>to slow my heart rate</i>

12:08.353 --> 12:11.314
so that I don't end up
in the ambulance.

12:11.314 --> 12:13.274
- Bladesmiths!

12:13.274 --> 12:15.235
You have 45 minutes remaining

12:15.235 --> 12:17.654
in this first round
of competition!

12:17.654 --> 12:19.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:19.822 --> 12:21.908
Here we go.
Alex is in the quench.

12:21.908 --> 12:24.452
- Ah, [bleep].

12:24.452 --> 12:26.663
It's like this.

12:26.663 --> 12:29.540
Got to be able
to grind through this.

12:29.540 --> 12:32.835
I don't have time
to mess around with this.

12:32.835 --> 12:35.838
<i>I need to grind some of</i>
<i>the warp out of the blade.</i>

12:35.838 --> 12:38.424
I don't want to go home.

12:38.424 --> 12:39.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:39.968 --> 12:41.719
- Damn, this isn't working out.

12:41.719 --> 12:45.265
- Bill is still trying to set
his hardenable steel

12:45.265 --> 12:48.643
into his softer, outer layer
to create a San Mai.

12:48.643 --> 12:49.852
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:49.852 --> 12:51.479
<i>- The clock is ticking.</i>

12:51.479 --> 12:53.273
It's starting
to make me nervous now.

12:53.273 --> 12:54.774
Two-hammer construction.
- Oh, yeah.

12:54.774 --> 12:56.651
Two hammers, there you go.
- Oh, no.

12:56.651 --> 12:57.777
- Yeah, there we go.

12:57.777 --> 13:00.655
- Yes! Yes! Yes!

13:00.655 --> 13:04.158
- And I have to still forge
the blade

13:04.158 --> 13:07.078
and try to get
that drawn out more.

13:07.078 --> 13:10.039
- Five minutes, bladesmiths!

13:10.039 --> 13:11.708
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:11.708 --> 13:12.834
- Delam.

13:12.834 --> 13:15.461
- Come on, Bill.

13:15.461 --> 13:17.588
- I'm going down fighting.

13:17.588 --> 13:20.383
- Ten, nine, eight,

13:20.383 --> 13:22.719
seven, six,

13:22.719 --> 13:27.724
five, four, three, two, one!

13:27.724 --> 13:30.727
Bladesmiths, shut down your
machines and drop your tools!

13:30.727 --> 13:33.313
This forging round is over!

13:33.313 --> 13:37.525
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:37.525 --> 13:39.277
- I hope the judges
can appreciate

13:39.277 --> 13:41.612
that I did everything
the old-fashioned way.

13:41.612 --> 13:43.781
<i>I don't really</i>
<i>appreciate welding.</i>

13:43.781 --> 13:45.742
<i>I like to do rivets.</i>

13:45.742 --> 13:48.661
I think welds are kind of ugly,
for the most part.

13:48.661 --> 13:50.913
[bleep] that welder.
[chuckles]

13:50.913 --> 13:54.625
- Bladesmiths, this was a very
difficult round one,

13:54.625 --> 13:58.212
really challenging your
problem-solving capabilities.

13:58.212 --> 14:01.424
Now it's time for the judges to
take a closer look at your work.

14:01.424 --> 14:03.134
Alex, you're up first.

14:03.134 --> 14:05.678
Please present your blade
to the judges.

14:05.678 --> 14:07.722
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:07.722 --> 14:11.017
<i>- Right off, I like</i>
<i>the profile. It's very nice.</i>

14:11.017 --> 14:15.146
It feels solid, other than
these little flakes back here.

14:15.146 --> 14:17.857
- Lining it up
at the choil here,

14:17.857 --> 14:21.110
you can see that edge
travels off to one side.

14:21.110 --> 14:23.654
[knife clattering]

14:23.654 --> 14:25.531
So you've got a warp
and a twist.

14:25.531 --> 14:27.617
- Yeah.

14:27.617 --> 14:29.494
- Mike, you're up.

14:29.494 --> 14:31.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:31.579 --> 14:33.247
<i>- One thing that I like</i>
<i>about this blade</i>

14:33.247 --> 14:36.084
is it's designed
for a stabbing test.

14:36.084 --> 14:38.753
So you have that
spear-like shape over there.

14:38.753 --> 14:40.671
I like that you have
a false edge on one side

14:40.671 --> 14:42.673
that will support the stab.

14:42.673 --> 14:45.134
- Mike...
[sighs]

14:45.134 --> 14:48.387
your profile on your grind
could be fixed.

14:48.387 --> 14:50.807
But there's still a lot
you can do with this.

14:50.807 --> 14:53.559
- Andrew, you know what to do.

14:53.559 --> 14:55.728
<i>- I'm gonna be</i>
<i>totally honest.</i>

14:55.728 --> 14:58.397
<i>MIG welding's about the easiest</i>
<i>welding there is out there.</i>

14:58.397 --> 15:00.358
I really would've liked
to have seen you

15:00.358 --> 15:03.861
maybe spend about ten minutes
and just figure it out.

15:03.861 --> 15:07.323
That could definitely help
you beef this blade up, okay?

15:07.323 --> 15:10.243
This is very lean.

15:10.243 --> 15:11.911
- Bill, you're up.

15:11.911 --> 15:16.124
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:16.124 --> 15:18.960
- You got wires
that are sticking up

15:18.960 --> 15:20.503
<i>on the ends that are loose.</i> I

15:20.503 --> 15:23.923
can wiggle the wires
inside the taco.

15:23.923 --> 15:26.384
So it's definitely
not welded up 100%...

15:26.384 --> 15:28.010
[metal clatters]

15:28.010 --> 15:29.929
Especially that piece.

15:29.929 --> 15:32.682
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:32.682 --> 15:35.893
There's really not much
I can say on how to fix this.

15:35.893 --> 15:36.894
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:36.894 --> 15:38.729
- Gentlemen...

15:38.729 --> 15:40.815
the judges have made
their final decision.

15:40.815 --> 15:43.067
The bladesmith leaving
the Forge is...

15:43.067 --> 15:46.821
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:46.821 --> 15:49.323
Bill.
Your blade did not make the cut.

15:49.323 --> 15:51.075
J. will explain.

15:51.075 --> 15:53.161
- Bill, we all
really appreciate the work

15:53.161 --> 15:55.329
you put
into that challenge.

15:55.329 --> 15:57.373
<i>But not having your high-carbon</i>
<i>steel forge-welded together,</i>

15:57.373 --> 16:00.042
it's the least-developed blade
we have presented to us today.

16:00.042 --> 16:02.837
So that's why
we're gonna let you go.

16:02.837 --> 16:05.298
- Bill, please
surrender your blade.

16:05.298 --> 16:07.049
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:07.049 --> 16:08.467
<i>- I do feel</i>
<i>a bit disappointed,</i>

16:08.467 --> 16:11.387
but I gave it my best shot.

16:11.387 --> 16:14.765
And I'm glad that I persisted
right up until the end.

16:14.765 --> 16:16.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:16.934 --> 16:19.187
- All right, gents.

16:19.187 --> 16:21.606
You've made it through a very
difficult round one. Good job.

16:21.606 --> 16:23.524
Now that your blades
have been tempered,

16:23.524 --> 16:25.568
it's time to turn them
into fully functional weapons

16:25.568 --> 16:27.570
by attaching handles to them,

16:27.570 --> 16:30.156
using the range of materials
provided in our pantry.

16:30.156 --> 16:33.409
You will have three hours
in which to complete this task.

16:33.409 --> 16:36.454
Now, you can use some of that
time to address flaws and issues

16:36.454 --> 16:38.289
that were identified
in your blades.

16:38.289 --> 16:40.166
Bladesmiths, do your best work,

16:40.166 --> 16:41.792
because when the time runs out

16:41.792 --> 16:43.628
and your blades
have been tested,

16:43.628 --> 16:46.339
one of you will be selected
to leave the Forge.

16:46.339 --> 16:48.925
Good luck.
Your time starts now.

16:48.925 --> 16:52.595
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:52.595 --> 16:55.932
<i>- I have constructed handles in</i>
<i>three hours and less at home.</i>

16:55.932 --> 16:58.059
That's why I'm pretty
confident here

16:58.059 --> 17:00.269
that I can do the same.

17:00.269 --> 17:04.690
<i>First, I need to fix some</i>
<i>deep divots and exclusions.</i>

17:04.690 --> 17:07.985
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:07.985 --> 17:09.028
Aah!

17:09.028 --> 17:10.863
[bleep] me.

17:10.863 --> 17:12.823
♪ ♪

17:12.823 --> 17:14.992
<i>I'm feeling a little</i>
<i>bit angry right now.</i>

17:14.992 --> 17:17.536
I had a really nice blade,
and I chewed up a lot of it.

17:17.536 --> 17:18.996
- Look at how much material
he's removed.

17:18.996 --> 17:20.623
- Yeah.

17:20.623 --> 17:22.500
- The whole shape
of that blade's changed.

17:22.500 --> 17:24.460
<i>- Hopefully I haven't</i>
<i>weakened it too much</i>

17:24.460 --> 17:27.171
<i>and it'll be enough</i>
<i>to withstand the challenge.</i>

17:27.171 --> 17:29.882
I think the luck of the Irish is
still gonna come through for me.

17:29.882 --> 17:31.884
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:31.884 --> 17:33.844
- First thing I need to do
is deal with the warps

17:33.844 --> 17:37.557
<i>and the mild steel that</i>
<i>hasn't been ground away yet.</i>

17:37.557 --> 17:39.475
- Alex's blade is very thick.

17:39.475 --> 17:42.770
It also has a lot of that
soft can on the outside of it.

17:42.770 --> 17:44.981
- That's the problem.

17:44.981 --> 17:48.401
It's gonna take quite a bit
of grinding to even that out.

17:48.401 --> 17:49.986
- Lot of grinding.

17:49.986 --> 17:52.363
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:52.363 --> 17:55.283
- I know that I got to make
this tang a little bit longer,

17:55.283 --> 17:58.160
<i>and give it</i>
<i>a little bit more mass.</i>

17:58.160 --> 18:01.747
It'll make for a more
structurally sound knife.

18:01.747 --> 18:04.292
All right. Here we go.

18:04.292 --> 18:06.502
The MIG welder
pissed me off last time.

18:06.502 --> 18:08.588
I didn't think I was gonna
have to come back to it.

18:08.588 --> 18:10.965
Here we go.
[grunts oddly]

18:10.965 --> 18:13.175
You can do it.

18:13.175 --> 18:16.053
- Right now I think Andrew's
relying a lot on the underdog

18:16.053 --> 18:18.347
and luck factor.

18:18.347 --> 18:21.267
- There we go.
- Yes!

18:21.267 --> 18:24.478
- You know, the welder and I are
pretty good friends right now.

18:24.478 --> 18:27.815
- Bladesmiths!
One hour has elapsed!

18:27.815 --> 18:31.152
- So I have my handle material--
stag horn.

18:31.152 --> 18:35.114
But I need to start drilling
the hole in the cross guard.

18:35.114 --> 18:37.658
<i>Without the guard,</i>
<i>the possibility of his hand</i>

18:37.658 --> 18:41.412
<i>slipping down on the blade</i>
<i>is a real safety concern.</i>

18:41.412 --> 18:43.539
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:43.539 --> 18:45.041
Ugh.

18:45.041 --> 18:46.834
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:46.834 --> 18:49.170
[bleep] damn it.

18:49.170 --> 18:51.797
<i>Leaning all my weight on it,</i>
<i>and it wouldn't go through.</i>

18:51.797 --> 18:53.382
[bleep] damn it!

18:53.382 --> 18:54.550
- Mike having a meltdown
right now?

18:54.550 --> 18:57.345
- [bleep].

18:57.345 --> 18:59.930
<i>I'm getting frustrated</i>

18:59.930 --> 19:03.225
'cause everything I try
seems to fail.

19:03.225 --> 19:05.102
[bleep].

19:05.102 --> 19:08.481
If I can't finish
this handle, I'm done.

19:08.481 --> 19:09.607
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:10.733 --> 19:12.860
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:12.860 --> 19:15.237
- Ugh.

19:15.237 --> 19:17.698
<i>Leaning all my weight on it,</i>
<i>and it wouldn't go through.</i>

19:17.698 --> 19:19.659
[bleep] damn it!

19:19.659 --> 19:21.452
I realize I'll have
to abandon the guard.

19:21.452 --> 19:24.163
It's gonna take way
too much time.

19:24.163 --> 19:26.457
- You have just 60 minutes
remaining

19:26.457 --> 19:28.000
to finish your weapons.

19:28.000 --> 19:30.336
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:30.336 --> 19:32.088
- Oh, the last thing
I would want Andrew

19:32.088 --> 19:34.632
to do is try to grind down
some of that weld.

19:34.632 --> 19:36.509
I'm sure it's a sketchy weld.

19:36.509 --> 19:38.761
He needs to leave as much
material there as possible.

19:38.761 --> 19:40.221
- I'm feeling great.

19:40.221 --> 19:42.223
<i>Now I have enough tang</i>

19:42.223 --> 19:44.725
to comfortably have enough room
for a hand on there.

19:44.725 --> 19:46.435
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:46.435 --> 19:49.230
Ugh!

19:49.230 --> 19:50.523
[bleep].

19:50.523 --> 19:53.109
That'll [bleep] [bleep] up.

19:53.109 --> 19:56.070
My tang broke off
inside the handle.

19:56.070 --> 19:59.031
<i>I have to weld</i>
<i>another tang to it,</i>

19:59.031 --> 20:01.659
and there's not much time
on the clock.

20:01.659 --> 20:04.370
<i>- I got my handle material.</i>

20:04.370 --> 20:06.288
Now I need
to start drilling a hole

20:06.288 --> 20:08.207
where I'm gonna put my tang.

20:08.207 --> 20:09.917
- What worries me
about what Alex is doing

20:09.917 --> 20:11.585
is he's drilling
a rectangular hole

20:11.585 --> 20:13.546
for a tang that's tapered.

20:13.546 --> 20:15.673
So he's gonna have
a lot of weight.

20:15.673 --> 20:17.383
- Now it's just a matter

20:17.383 --> 20:19.719
of thinning out my tang
just slightly.

20:19.719 --> 20:22.722
- Don't take the tang down.

20:22.722 --> 20:24.849
- No, no, no, no.
Don't grind.

20:24.849 --> 20:26.392
- I hate seeing the snip fit,

20:26.392 --> 20:28.352
instead
of removing more wood,

20:28.352 --> 20:31.147
removing
more steel from the tang.

20:31.147 --> 20:33.065
<i>- I'm happy with that.</i>

20:33.065 --> 20:35.776
And now I'm gonna
assemble everything.

20:35.776 --> 20:38.237
<i>- Finally get the handle</i>
<i>and the pommel</i>

20:38.237 --> 20:40.197
<i>fitted onto the tang.</i>

20:40.197 --> 20:44.034
But I'm so flustered,
had so many setbacks.

20:44.034 --> 20:45.703
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:45.703 --> 20:48.873
And now I need
to sharpen the blade.

20:48.873 --> 20:50.916
Oh!

20:50.916 --> 20:53.836
<i>Going around the hamster wheel</i>
<i>at this time.</i>

20:53.836 --> 20:55.463
<i>Matter of fact,</i>
<i>I think I quit running</i>

20:55.463 --> 20:57.298
<i>and the wheel's</i>
<i>still going around,</i>

20:57.298 --> 20:59.592
so I'm going like this,
you know?

20:59.592 --> 21:03.262
<i>I keep grinding, hoping that</i>
<i>an edge will magically appear,</i>

21:03.262 --> 21:07.475
and I'll test it, and it'll be,
like, miraculously sharp.

21:07.475 --> 21:10.394
- Based on the constructions
that you've seen here,

21:10.394 --> 21:12.229
is there a blade on this floor

21:12.229 --> 21:14.482
that you would feel
comfortable using?

21:14.482 --> 21:16.567
- Absolutely.
- Which one is that?

21:16.567 --> 21:19.195
- The one I'm wearing.
- [laughs]

21:19.195 --> 21:24.283
You have only 30 minutes
remaining to finish your work!

21:24.283 --> 21:25.659
Then one of you's going home!

21:25.659 --> 21:28.204
<i>- I would love to be Wil.</i>

21:28.204 --> 21:30.456
I want to tell people they got
a little bit of time left.

21:30.456 --> 21:31.832
It's great. I want to do it.

21:31.832 --> 21:33.834
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:33.834 --> 21:35.961
Now I need to start heating
the very end of the tang,

21:35.961 --> 21:39.048
so it holds together
as one single mechanical lock.

21:39.048 --> 21:40.758
This should be pretty easy.

21:40.758 --> 21:46.222
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:46.222 --> 21:48.098
<i>The butt cap</i>
<i>is bouncing everywhere</i>

21:48.098 --> 21:49.767
<i>because I didn't have time</i>
<i>to anchor it.</i>

21:49.767 --> 21:51.477
Oh, this ain't working.

21:51.477 --> 21:53.479
- That better be
a tight-fitting tang.

21:53.479 --> 21:56.106
- You would hope.

21:56.106 --> 21:59.443
- Yeah, you don't want
no rattling around in there.

21:59.443 --> 22:01.445
- Not the way
I wanted things to go.

22:01.445 --> 22:04.990
My heart's racing.
I'm freaking out.

22:04.990 --> 22:09.119
<i>At this point, I'm just</i>
<i>rage-hammering on this.</i>

22:09.119 --> 22:11.163
Oh, that's ugly.
It'll hold.

22:11.163 --> 22:13.082
It works.

22:13.082 --> 22:15.668
It's like Fonzie
hitting the jukebox, you know?

22:15.668 --> 22:16.877
He hits it, and it works.

22:16.877 --> 22:19.213
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:19.213 --> 22:21.215
- Got to make this work.

22:21.215 --> 22:23.384
- Andrew's welding more steel
onto his tang.

22:23.384 --> 22:25.010
<i>- I don't want it</i>
<i>to be short,</i>

22:25.010 --> 22:27.263
so I got to add
more material to it.

22:27.263 --> 22:29.473
Yeah. It's getting there.

22:29.473 --> 22:31.475
- This is the longest he's been
at the welder yet.

22:31.475 --> 22:33.561
It's giving me hope.

22:33.561 --> 22:35.771
- It's ugly. It might work.

22:35.771 --> 22:39.066
- It looks like a sea urchin
at that junction right there.

22:39.066 --> 22:41.443
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:41.443 --> 22:43.320
- Ooh. [groans]

22:43.320 --> 22:45.739
- The weld break again?
- Yep.

22:45.739 --> 22:48.659
<i>- I can't weld. I've lost</i>
<i>all faith in the welding.</i>

22:48.659 --> 22:53.163
I have to work with what I have
and use the original tang.

22:53.163 --> 22:56.667
It may not be my best work,
but I'm getting the blade in.

22:56.667 --> 22:58.586
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:58.586 --> 23:00.379
- Ten, nine,

23:00.379 --> 23:02.923
eight, seven, six,

23:02.923 --> 23:06.468
five, four, three,

23:06.468 --> 23:08.220
two, one!

23:08.220 --> 23:10.472
Shut down your machines,
drop your tools.

23:10.472 --> 23:13.559
This round is over.

23:13.559 --> 23:16.812
<i>- I'm not feeling good at all.</i>
<i>I'm unhappy.</i>

23:16.812 --> 23:20.149
My stack's up about end
of the line, I do believe.

23:20.149 --> 23:22.109
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:22.109 --> 23:24.904
- Bladesmiths, this is
a sharpness test.

23:24.904 --> 23:26.780
To see how sharp
your weapons are,

23:26.780 --> 23:29.742
I will attempt to cut open
these heavy-duty leather bags.

23:29.742 --> 23:31.493
Alex, you're up first.
You ready?

23:31.493 --> 23:34.121
- No.
- Let's do this anyway.

23:34.121 --> 23:37.166
<i>- I'm the first one to have</i>
<i>their blade tested,</i>

23:37.166 --> 23:38.918
so I'm also the first one
to freak out.

23:38.918 --> 23:40.836
<i>My heart is really pounding.</i>

23:40.836 --> 23:45.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:47.051 --> 23:48.886
[exhales deeply]

23:48.886 --> 23:50.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:50.220 --> 23:53.933
- Okay, Alex, it has the edge

23:53.933 --> 23:56.393
that definitely will cut
through the bag.

23:56.393 --> 24:00.272
You've got the mass that
definitely dug into the apron.

24:00.272 --> 24:04.985
Overall, I think
your blade will cut. Good job.

24:04.985 --> 24:07.029
- Thank you.
- Mike, let's do this.

24:07.029 --> 24:08.113
- Let's do it.

24:08.113 --> 24:09.990
<i>I'm quite nervous.</i>

24:09.990 --> 24:12.743
<i>I didn't get a good edge</i>
<i>on it.</i>

24:12.743 --> 24:15.955
I'm just afraid the blade
will bounce off the bag.

24:15.955 --> 24:17.498
[groans]

24:17.498 --> 24:22.670
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:24.755 --> 24:26.632
[exhales deeply]

24:26.632 --> 24:28.676
- Okay, Mike, you have
the right edge geometry

24:28.676 --> 24:30.886
to slash into the bag.

24:30.886 --> 24:33.347
My only issue is the way
the handle feels in my hand.

24:33.347 --> 24:34.932
It's really comfortable

24:34.932 --> 24:38.185
to hold the blade this way,
not this way.

24:38.185 --> 24:41.021
Otherwise, your blade will cut.

24:41.021 --> 24:43.232
Good job. Andrew, ready?

24:43.232 --> 24:44.525
- I'm ready.
- Let's do this.

24:44.525 --> 24:51.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:58.956 --> 25:03.460
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:03.460 --> 25:05.838
Well, Andrew,
that's a small handle, buddy.

25:05.838 --> 25:09.008
- It is.
- It's hard to hold on to.

25:09.008 --> 25:11.760
But it's got enough grip to be
able to cut through the bags.

25:11.760 --> 25:13.262
Your blade will cut.

25:13.262 --> 25:15.472
- Thank you.
- Good job.

25:15.472 --> 25:18.267
- I think everyone performed
equally in the slice test.

25:18.267 --> 25:21.228
<i>Now comes the dreaded</i>
<i>oil drum test.</i>

25:21.228 --> 25:25.357
- Bladesmiths, I'm going to
quite violently stab downward

25:25.357 --> 25:29.111
into this heavy-duty steel
drum's lid three times.

25:29.111 --> 25:31.905
Alex, ready?

25:31.905 --> 25:33.949
Yeah.

25:33.949 --> 25:37.036
- With my rage-hammering
to get this handle pinned on,

25:37.036 --> 25:40.330
I'm wondering how well
it's gonna hold.

25:40.330 --> 25:47.254
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:50.174 --> 25:52.760
- Oh.
[chuckles]

25:52.760 --> 25:54.845
- Now, Alex, it's a little bit
tough to hold on to,

25:54.845 --> 25:57.181
between the thickness back here

25:57.181 --> 25:59.975
and the tip and handle being
off-centered from each other.

25:59.975 --> 26:02.394
You do have some shine,
you do have some rolled spots,

26:02.394 --> 26:03.979
but it's not the whole edge.

26:03.979 --> 26:06.690
Everything's still tight.
Nicely done.

26:06.690 --> 26:09.318
- Thank you.
- Mike, you're next.

26:09.318 --> 26:11.737
How do you feel?
- A little nervous.

26:11.737 --> 26:13.989
I had not completed the guard.

26:13.989 --> 26:16.533
<i>The possibility of his hand</i>
<i>slipping down on the blade</i>

26:16.533 --> 26:19.745
causing injury
is a real concern.

26:19.745 --> 26:24.541
- Being that this is stabbing
a steel blade into a steel drum

26:24.541 --> 26:27.669
and I really like my hands,
I'm gonna add a blade stop.

26:27.669 --> 26:29.546
- Thank you.

26:29.546 --> 26:32.466
- But the blade stop's gonna
be up above your handle,

26:32.466 --> 26:34.885
so it can't give
any extra support,

26:34.885 --> 26:37.679
which would be unfair
to the other contestants.

26:37.679 --> 26:39.640
<i>- I'm concerned</i>
<i>with the structural integrity</i>

26:39.640 --> 26:41.391
<i>of my blade.</i>

26:41.391 --> 26:43.310
It's either gonna
make or break.

26:43.310 --> 26:45.354
<i>Maybe the luck of the Irish</i>
<i>is on my side.</i>

26:45.354 --> 26:46.396
We'll see.

26:46.396 --> 26:47.189
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:48.315 --> 26:50.442
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:50.442 --> 26:52.528
<i>- I'm concerned</i>
<i>with the structural integrity</i>

26:52.528 --> 26:54.196
<i>of my blade.</i>

26:54.196 --> 26:55.656
It's either gonna
make or break.

26:55.656 --> 27:02.579
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:08.669 --> 27:13.215
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:13.215 --> 27:16.009
- Mike, she held up.
- Wow.

27:16.009 --> 27:19.346
- You did pick up
a curve, though.

27:19.346 --> 27:22.432
It was in line
with your handle,

27:22.432 --> 27:24.142
and now it's off.

27:24.142 --> 27:27.020
Overall, it'll stab.

27:27.020 --> 27:29.273
Good job.
- Thank you.

27:29.273 --> 27:31.650
- Andrew, you ready to put
the elf knife to the test?

27:31.650 --> 27:33.819
- I'm ready.

27:33.819 --> 27:36.488
<i>I'm nervous, not only about</i>
<i>my blade and the welds,</i>

27:36.488 --> 27:38.657
but I don't want a piece
of my knife to fly into my face,

27:38.657 --> 27:40.826
or anybody else's face.

27:40.826 --> 27:47.791
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:51.336 --> 27:53.380
- What the--

27:53.380 --> 27:55.382
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:55.382 --> 27:57.843
- Penetrated very well.

27:57.843 --> 27:59.887
Your edge...

27:59.887 --> 28:03.891
<i>we've lost pieces of the edge</i>
<i>going into that steel.</i>

28:03.891 --> 28:07.102
The handle wasn't an issue,
as far as would've been nice

28:07.102 --> 28:08.770
to have a little more mass
to hold on to.

28:08.770 --> 28:10.939
But it's loose now.

28:10.939 --> 28:12.107
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:12.107 --> 28:14.818
But all in all, good job.

28:14.818 --> 28:18.614
- All right, bladesmiths, the
judges have a decision to make.

28:18.614 --> 28:24.119
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:24.119 --> 28:28.123
- We'll start with Alex's blade
on the end.

28:28.123 --> 28:30.375
<i>- Alex has a lot</i>
<i>of symmetry issues,</i>

28:30.375 --> 28:32.628
<i>a lot of gapping issues.</i>

28:32.628 --> 28:34.504
The handle, a little fat
in the back

28:34.504 --> 28:37.966
for what I was doing
with the stabbing.

28:37.966 --> 28:40.719
- Among all the Bowie blades
we've had in the stabbing test,

28:40.719 --> 28:43.388
this one penetrated
the deepest.

28:43.388 --> 28:46.433
<i>Yes, the blade is</i>
<i>kind of offset on the handle,</i>

28:46.433 --> 28:48.268
<i>but overall, I think</i>

28:48.268 --> 28:50.437
he did a good job
with this particular blade.

28:50.437 --> 28:52.731
- Let's get into the details
of Mike's blade.

28:52.731 --> 28:54.441
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:54.441 --> 28:56.234
<i>- When Mike</i>
<i>was trying to get</i>

28:56.234 --> 28:58.528
<i>all that forge work</i>
<i>out of his blade,</i>

28:58.528 --> 29:01.239
he wound up taking everything
out of the ricasso.

29:01.239 --> 29:03.200
And the fact that he has
no guard on here,

29:03.200 --> 29:07.037
it's just so incomplete.

29:07.037 --> 29:09.748
- The issue is the thinness
down here.

29:09.748 --> 29:12.751
I honestly was concerned,
stabbing into the barrel,

29:12.751 --> 29:15.087
that this knife was gonna
fold over in half.

29:15.087 --> 29:18.590
But it held together much more
so than I thought it would.

29:18.590 --> 29:22.928
<i>- Let's move on to our next</i>
<i>bladesmith, and that's Andrew.</i>

29:22.928 --> 29:24.972
<i>- There was a bit</i>
<i>of a warp before.</i>

29:24.972 --> 29:27.474
<i>Now it's completely</i>
<i>out of alignment.</i>

29:27.474 --> 29:30.811
But then you go to the handle.
Everything's loose.

29:30.811 --> 29:32.688
Guard's loose now.

29:32.688 --> 29:35.857
Pommel's loose now.
It's just gonna get worse.

29:35.857 --> 29:39.236
- We have issues with his blade.
It had chunks over here.

29:39.236 --> 29:41.405
The handle came across.

29:41.405 --> 29:44.574
But it was sharp enough
to cut on the sharpness test.

29:44.574 --> 29:46.284
- So, Doug, have you made
your final decision?

29:46.284 --> 29:47.452
- Yes, I have.

29:47.452 --> 29:48.578
- Dave?
- Yep.

29:48.578 --> 29:49.746
- J.?
- Yeah.

29:49.746 --> 29:51.164
- Let's go tell our smiths.

29:51.164 --> 29:53.333
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:53.333 --> 29:56.336
All right, gents, the judges
have made a final decision.

29:56.336 --> 29:58.714
It's time for one of you
to leave the Forge.

29:58.714 --> 30:01.383
The bladesmith leaving
the forge is...

30:01.383 --> 30:03.885
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:03.885 --> 30:05.679
Andrew.

30:05.679 --> 30:09.099
Your blade did not make the cut.
J. will explain.

30:09.099 --> 30:11.226
- Andrew, you made a heck
of a comeback.

30:11.226 --> 30:13.103
But at the end of the day,

30:13.103 --> 30:15.522
there's pieces completely
missing from the edge.

30:15.522 --> 30:17.607
<i>And then you already had</i>
<i>a warp,</i>

30:17.607 --> 30:19.609
<i>but it's actually bent</i>
<i>even further</i>

30:19.609 --> 30:21.611
<i>from the stress</i>
<i>of hitting that steel.</i>

30:21.611 --> 30:23.447
<i>Probably a few more whacks</i>
<i>in the strength test,</i>

30:23.447 --> 30:25.449
we'd have had a folder,
Just going the wrong way.

30:25.449 --> 30:27.617
So that's why
we're gonna let you go.

30:27.617 --> 30:29.536
- All right, Andrew.
Please surrender your weapon.

30:29.536 --> 30:31.246
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:31.246 --> 30:32.831
<i>- I'm a little disappointed.</i>

30:32.831 --> 30:35.042
- Good game.

30:35.042 --> 30:37.127
- I wanted it bad, but just got
hung up in a few spots.

30:37.127 --> 30:38.378
- Good fight, brother.
- Thanks.

30:38.378 --> 30:40.297
- Good fight.

30:40.297 --> 30:41.798
<i>- I feel this is</i>
<i>a test of a lot of things--</i>

30:41.798 --> 30:45.385
character, skill,
problem-solving.

30:45.385 --> 30:47.345
The first thing I do
when I get home,

30:47.345 --> 30:49.014
I'm getting
right back to knife making.

30:49.014 --> 30:50.891
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:50.891 --> 30:52.934
- Mike, Alex, congratulations.

30:52.934 --> 30:55.437
You've made it into the final
round of this competition,

30:55.437 --> 30:57.856
which means that you're both
one step closer to the title

30:57.856 --> 31:00.650
of "Forged in Fire" champion
and a check for ten grand.

31:00.650 --> 31:02.486
All you have to do now

31:02.486 --> 31:05.197
is re-create an iconic weapon
from history.

31:05.197 --> 31:06.782
That weapon is...

31:06.782 --> 31:08.492
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:08.492 --> 31:11.328
The horseman's axe.
both: Oh.

31:11.328 --> 31:14.456
<i>- Used by mounted knights</i>
<i>in armies, the horseman's axe</i>

31:14.456 --> 31:16.208
<i>became the weapon of choice</i>
<i>after body armor</i>

31:16.208 --> 31:18.710
<i>made swords less effective.</i>

31:18.710 --> 31:20.712
<i>The heavier axe,</i>
<i>with its concave blade,</i>

31:20.712 --> 31:23.173
<i>allowed horsemen to strike</i>
<i>more effective blows,</i>

31:23.173 --> 31:27.177
<i>using a sweeping overhead</i>
<i>stroke that penetrated armor.</i>

31:27.177 --> 31:29.221
<i>Early depictions</i>
<i>of medieval warfare</i>

31:29.221 --> 31:31.723
<i>shows the axe cleaving</i>
<i>an opponent's helmet,</i>

31:31.723 --> 31:33.141
<i>delivering a fatal strike.</i>

31:33.141 --> 31:35.060
<i>In the film "Sleepy Hollow,"</i>

31:35.060 --> 31:38.647
<i>the headless horseman</i>
<i>wields a horseman's axe.</i>

31:38.647 --> 31:40.774
First and foremost,
your axes must be

31:40.774 --> 31:42.776
an all-steel construction.

31:42.776 --> 31:47.239
Your handle must include
a flange-style pommel and guard

31:47.239 --> 31:49.991
and include a belt hook.

31:49.991 --> 31:51.493
You will have five days.

31:51.493 --> 31:53.078
At the end of five days,
you will return

31:53.078 --> 31:54.329
and present
your finished weapons

31:54.329 --> 31:56.373
to our panel of expert judges.

31:56.373 --> 31:59.376
Only after they've submitted
them to a series of brutal tests

31:59.376 --> 32:01.628
will they declare one of you
the "Forged in Fire" champion

32:01.628 --> 32:04.381
who also leaves with
that check for ten grand.

32:04.381 --> 32:07.425
Do your best work. You're both
talented bladesmiths.

32:07.425 --> 32:10.137
Show us $10,000 blades
that you can be proud of.

32:10.137 --> 32:12.389
We'll see you in five days.
Good luck.

32:12.389 --> 32:14.182
- Good luck.
- Good luck.

32:14.182 --> 32:17.310
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:17.310 --> 32:19.479
<i>- It was a challenge getting</i>
<i>through to the finals,</i>

32:19.479 --> 32:21.398
but I'm just glad
to be back home.

32:21.398 --> 32:23.525
<i>I know I'm good enough</i>
<i>to be in the finals,</i>

32:23.525 --> 32:25.152
and I plan to take home
the championship.

32:25.152 --> 32:27.988
I'm getting ready.
It's time to make an axe.

32:27.988 --> 32:29.990
It's definitely a unique weapon.

32:29.990 --> 32:31.908
<i>I've done axes before--</i>
<i>I'm just a little nervous</i>

32:31.908 --> 32:34.411
about the all-metal
construction of it.

32:34.411 --> 32:37.205
<i>I've got this big block</i>
<i>of 4140.</i>

32:37.205 --> 32:40.125
It's a really good
impact steel.

32:40.125 --> 32:43.170
<i>If anything's gonna hold up</i>
<i>to hitting something,</i>

32:43.170 --> 32:46.590
it's gonna be that
4140 head, 4140 body.

32:46.590 --> 32:48.967
Yeah.

32:48.967 --> 32:51.511
<i>My goal for day one</i>
<i>is to upset the round bar,</i>

32:51.511 --> 32:55.223
get it nice and wide,
and then start drawing it out.

32:55.223 --> 32:58.810
I may have five days, but if the
competition taught me anything,

32:58.810 --> 33:00.520
<i>work fast, work diligently,</i>

33:00.520 --> 33:04.024
in case I run
into a last-minute issue.

33:04.024 --> 33:05.317
We're getting there.

33:05.317 --> 33:08.528
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:08.528 --> 33:11.823
- I'm ready to get started.
I'm making a horseman's axe.

33:11.823 --> 33:13.325
It's got a curved head
on one end

33:13.325 --> 33:15.118
<i>and a spike on the other.</i>

33:15.118 --> 33:16.661
and a belt hook
so that they could carry it

33:16.661 --> 33:18.163
while they were riding.

33:18.163 --> 33:20.332
I can cut that.

33:20.332 --> 33:24.085
<i>My overall plan</i>
<i>is to do a two-piece head</i>

33:24.085 --> 33:27.672
and then attach it
separately to the handle.

33:27.672 --> 33:29.758
<i>The hardest part</i>
<i>of this weapon's gonna be</i>

33:29.758 --> 33:33.845
not being afraid to continue
in fear of making some mistake.

33:33.845 --> 33:35.889
<i>I can't have</i>
<i>analysis paralysis.</i>

33:35.889 --> 33:39.935
I can't analyze the problem
to the point where I do nothing.

33:39.935 --> 33:43.313
<i>I have to trust my better</i>
<i>judgment and just get it done.</i>

33:43.313 --> 33:47.484
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:47.484 --> 33:50.362
<i>- I'm hoping to get the axe</i>
<i>spread out, get it shaped,</i>

33:50.362 --> 33:52.239
and start drifting
the eye today.

33:52.239 --> 33:55.033
Getting that spread out
another inch and a half

33:55.033 --> 33:58.954
to be past minimum
is my biggest challenge.

33:58.954 --> 34:03.708
This is the biggest axe I've
ever made by about 2 1/2 inches.

34:03.708 --> 34:05.919
I'm nervous.
All right. Here I go.

34:05.919 --> 34:07.545
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:07.545 --> 34:09.756
I'm cutting
these little nubs in,

34:09.756 --> 34:14.344
hoping that I can open them up
this way to add some width.

34:14.344 --> 34:16.346
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:16.346 --> 34:17.847
[bleep].

34:17.847 --> 34:20.100
My plan didn't work.

34:20.100 --> 34:24.479
This is not gonna
become 5 1/2 or 6 inches.

34:24.479 --> 34:26.648
I'm gonna have to start over.

34:26.648 --> 34:29.609
<i>And I'm freaking out.</i>
<i>I just don't have the time.</i>

34:29.609 --> 34:30.986
[sighs]

34:30.986 --> 34:31.420
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:33.029 --> 34:37.075
- This is not gonna become
5 1/2 or 6 inches.

34:37.075 --> 34:39.953
I'm gonna have to start over.
But I'm keeping the spike.

34:39.953 --> 34:42.664
My plan now is
to cut it right here,

34:42.664 --> 34:45.875
and I'm gonna
forge-weld this to this.

34:45.875 --> 34:48.670
It hurts to cut off
the work I've got so far,

34:48.670 --> 34:50.839
<i>but I don't have time</i>
<i>to dink around with it.</i>

34:50.839 --> 34:53.967
<i>It's definitely better</i>
<i>than doing this on day five.</i>

34:53.967 --> 34:56.720
<i>- Today I'm working</i>
<i>on the belt hook.</i>

34:56.720 --> 34:59.973
The plan is to use this piece
of garage door spring,

34:59.973 --> 35:03.727
<i>kind of give it a little ball</i>
<i>on the end and have it bent.</i>

35:03.727 --> 35:05.729
That ought to do.

35:05.729 --> 35:07.564
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:07.564 --> 35:09.816
<i>Quenching the shaft,</i>
<i>I used a torch</i>

35:09.816 --> 35:13.278
<i>because I thought I'd have</i>
<i>a difficult time in the forge.</i>

35:13.278 --> 35:19.242
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:20.827 --> 35:22.287
I think it's hard.

35:22.287 --> 35:24.247
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:24.247 --> 35:26.916
<i>Next, I'm gonna peen</i>
<i>in the belt hook.</i>

35:26.916 --> 35:29.127
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:29.127 --> 35:32.714
<i>The belt hook doesn't fit</i>
<i>snugly like I was hoping.</i>

35:32.714 --> 35:35.008
<i>The last thing I want to do</i>
<i>is to weld it,</i>

35:35.008 --> 35:37.677
because it's a hard material,

35:37.677 --> 35:41.056
<i>and the extra heat from welding</i>
<i>can make the metal brittle.</i>

35:41.056 --> 35:44.684
But I'm exhausted.
I can barely think straight.

35:44.684 --> 35:46.561
Sometimes you got to do
what you got to do.

35:46.561 --> 35:52.317
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:52.317 --> 35:55.028
- I'm happy. I've got something
that's solid,

35:55.028 --> 35:56.529
and it looks like an axe.

35:56.529 --> 35:59.032
I got the belt hook
peened over.

35:59.032 --> 36:01.326
Now I need to heat-treat.
It's a tense moment.

36:01.326 --> 36:04.204
I'm gonna heat-treat
one section and the other.

36:04.204 --> 36:05.747
<i>Heat treat</i>
<i>will make or break my edge,</i>

36:05.747 --> 36:08.124
<i>literally and figuratively.</i>

36:08.124 --> 36:11.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:11.544 --> 36:13.755
I don't see any cracks.

36:13.755 --> 36:16.049
I don't want to hurry up
and rush the part

36:16.049 --> 36:17.801
<i>where the two different types</i>
<i>of steel join,</i>

36:17.801 --> 36:19.844
<i>because that can pop the weld,</i>

36:19.844 --> 36:22.097
and, really, there's not much
I can do from there.

36:22.097 --> 36:27.811
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:27.811 --> 36:29.521
[chuckles]

36:29.521 --> 36:31.856
Oh.

36:31.856 --> 36:33.900
<i>Now that</i>
<i>the heat treat's done,</i>

36:33.900 --> 36:35.860
<i>I'm testing my weapon</i>
<i>on a piece of sheet metal.</i>

36:35.860 --> 36:37.570
<i>I want to see what kind</i>
<i>of damage it'll do.</i>

36:37.570 --> 36:42.742
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:42.742 --> 36:44.244
Nothing loose.

36:44.244 --> 36:49.165
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:49.165 --> 36:51.710
It will bend.

36:51.710 --> 36:54.003
<i>- Today I'm gonna do</i>
<i>some assembly.</i>

36:54.003 --> 36:56.756
<i>I'm adding</i>
<i>the sassafras handle.</i>

36:56.756 --> 36:58.550
<i>It finishes beautifully.</i>

36:58.550 --> 37:01.302
It's soft. It's relatively
easy to work with.

37:01.302 --> 37:03.304
The handle's complete.

